@misc{whitmore_warren_wildlife_2022,
	title = {{WILDLIFE} {TRUST} {ADDRESSES} {FARMERS}’ {CONCERNS} {OVER} {ISLE} {OF} {WIGHT} {BEAVER} {INTRODUCTION}},
	url = {https://www.islandecho.co.uk/wildlife-trust-addresses-farmers-concerns-over-isle-of-wight-beaver-introduction/},
	abstract = {More than 70 farmers and landowners attended a meeting organised by the NFU (National Farmers' Union) about beaver introduction on Tuesday 5th April.

The meeting took place at The Chequers Inn, near Rookley, and helped farmers to understand the impact that a beaver introduction by Hampshire and Isle of Wight Wildlife Trust (HIWWT) could have on the farmed landscape of the Isle of Wight, should it be licensed.

The Wildlife Trust’s beaver officer outlined how beaver impacts could be managed, with measures including:

 	electric fencing of crops
 	sandpaper paint or galvanised fencing to protect trees
 	removal of trees and other sources of food from certain areas to discourage beaver establishment
 	reinforcement of riverbanks with stone or galvanised mesh to discourage burrowing.

Farmers from the Tay catchment in Scotland, where there are more than 1,000 beavers, and farmers from the Stour, in Kent, joined the meeting virtually, sharing their experiences of living with wild populations of beavers. The meeting was also addressed by the NFU’s national adviser on species reintroductions.

Those attending the meeting learned of significant damage to low lying arable land, like that in the Arreton Valley, caused by the burrowing and damming activities of beaver, graphically illustrated by photographic evidence.

Damage to public access routes was highlighted. Concerns were raised about where responsibility and culpability for injury would fall if damage by beavers led to the collapse of footpaths or bridleways on a farmer’s land - a further cost someone must take responsibility for.



Isle of Wight NFU chair Robyn Munt, of Parkwater Farm, Newport, said:
“Should a licence be granted, there would need to be intense monitoring of beaver activity by HIWWT within the entire Eastern Yar catchment. What remains unclear is who would cover the cost of these management options in the long term. HIWWT must demonstrate its ability to take responsibility for such costs during a five-year or 10-year licence period. However, beyond that, being a charitable organisation, it can only make assurances and cannot commit to financial responsibility in perpetuity if beavers were to spread across the Island.

“The NFU is lobbying for the managers of beaver projects to take full responsibility for the cost of such projects in the long term. This would include the costs of an exit strategy, should unmanageable conflicts arise. Importantly, the NFU is asking Government to ensure that every beaver project establishes a steering group with farmer representation within each steering group. We will be looking for the same assurances around licence being drawn up for the Island beaver project.”},
	language = {en-GB},
	urldate = {2024-03-29},
	author = {{Whitmore, Warren}},
	month = apr,
	year = {2022},
	note = {Section: Latest News},
}

